Yobe State Police Command has disclosed that its operatives, in a joint operation, have raided a drug zone in Damaturu where 209 parcels of weed, known as ‘Indian hemp’ were recovered. Assistant Superintendent of Police, Dungus Abdulkarim, the Command’s Public Relations Officers disclosed this in a statement made available to DAILY POST on Monday. The Command expressed worry over the rising level of drug intake among youths, which it said apart from causing health challenges, promotes crime and criminality in the society. “Drug intake and smoking of Indian hemp (Cannabis Sativa) embroidered our youth and as such lose the milk of human kindness in them and at slightest opportunity take to crime. “The Yobe State Police Command had on 27th February, 2022, along with other sister security agencies, cordoned and searched an isolated building at the outskirts of Damaturu town. “In the course of the search that lasted for about 30 minutes, 209 parcels of weed, suspected to be (Indian hemp) were recovered from the building, but the occupant of the house was not found”, the statement said. The Command, however, noted that its operatives are on the trail of the suspected owner of the exhibits,, assuring that sooner than later he will be apprehended and made to face prosecution. “Meanwhile, the Command assures the State of its commitment in ensuring security and public safety, while the recovered substance will be handed over to the National Drugs Law Enforcement Agency (NDLEA) Yobe State Command for analysis and custody, pending the outcome of investigation”, it said.